    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.21.15"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">92 Neihardt Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">CHICAGO ∙ BOSTON ∙ ATLANTA ∙ DALLAS ∙ SAN FRANCISCO ∙ LONDON ∙ TORONTO ∙ BOMBAY ∙ CALCUTTA ∙ MADRAS ∙ MELBOURNE ∙ SHANGHAI ∙ MANILA
                    
                    THE MACMILLAN COMPANY
                    
                    CABLE ADDRESS
                    PACHAMAC NEW YORK</hi>
                    
                    <hi rend="italics">Publishers</hi>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">TELEPHONE
                    ALGONQUIN 4-2100
                    
                    SIXTY ∙ FIFTH AVENUE ∙ NEW YORK
                    
                    GEORGE P. BRETT, JR., PRESIDENT
                    H.S. LATHAM, VICE PRESIDENT
                    
                    E.L. MEAD, SECRETARY
                    R.M. BRETT, TREASURER</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>February 25, 1946</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I too had hoped that this would be the year for the publication of the <hi rend="underline">Cycle</hi>, but I am afraid it is improbable. The paper situation and the manufacturing situation are really worse than they were during the war. When I tell you that we have postponed, until some indefinite time in the future, thirty-seven books which were on our spring list simply because we could not get the paper, you can see how serious this is. Publishers are in the business to make and sell books, and it hurts them,when they have good literature which they wish to put upon the market, not to be able to do anything about it.</p>
                
                <p>Please don't become discouraged. We have every reason for being discouraged ourselves, but we are not. We know that in time this thing will right itself, and that it will again be possible to produce books to meet demands. We are committed to the publication of the Cycle in one volume, and we shall do it just as soon as conditions make it at all possible to do it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed>HS Latham</signed>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>4917 South Blackstone Ave.</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Chicago 15, Illinois</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <note>HSL.KK</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
